name "fig:Effect-of-contact"

\end_inset

Single leg adhesion force measurements of ladybug beetle (
\emph on
Coccinella septempuctata
\emph default
) on glass and PFOTS substrates in air and underwater conditions.
 Values represent peak force of a distal pad pulled off from each substrate.
 Three types of contact are seen in underwater experiments and are represented
 separately: 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
bubble
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
no bubble
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
bad contact
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 Stars represent theoretical predictions of adhesion force calculated from
 the capillary bridge model, where hair diameter = 4 Œºm, pad diameter =
 200 Œºm, hair height = 40 Œºm, N
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
hairs
\end_layout

\end_inset

 = 500, V
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
fluid
\end_layout

\end_inset

 = 4.2 fL and V
\begin_inset script subscript

\begin_layout Plain Layout
bubble
\end_layout

\end_inset

 = 1.2 nL.
 Interfacial tension of the adhesive fluid in air and water are assumed
 to be 24 mN/m and 48 mN/m respectively and water surface tension is 72
 mN/m.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Apart from the three predicted contact types, we also observed an additional
 fourth type of contact which sometimes occurs underwater, labeled as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
bad contact
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

.
 In this scenario, the ventral view recordings show that the hairs don't
 appear to contact well with the substrate, unlike the other three contact
 types.
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
Bad contact
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 shows no adhesion with either glass or PFOTS substrate.
 While it's not completely clear why such a contact occurs, there can be
 two possible reasons.
 First, the hairs could get bundled due to a small air meniscus within the
 hairs, resulting in their disorientation.
 Second, a thin water layer at the substrate interface might not be drained
 out to allow the hairs to make contact with the substrate, resulting in
 a loss of adhesion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Capillary Bridge Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We model the hairy pad as an array of 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 cylindrical rods of length, 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, and diameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{h}$
\end_inset

, fixed to a flat circular pad of diameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}$
\end_inset

, as shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The hairs and the pad are assumed to be perfectly rigid, for simplicity.
 The tip of each hair has an adhesive fluid of volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{f}$
\end_inset

, making contact with the substrate.
 The fluid is pinned to the circumference of the hair and forms a capillary
 bridge of height, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Similar to our experiments, we consider three types of contacts for the
 pad: 1) 
\emph on
In air
\emph default
, 2) 
\emph on
Underwater: no bubble
\emph default
 and 3) 
\emph on
Underwater: bubble
\emph default
.
 In the third case, a bubble of volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{b}$
\end_inset

, is trapped between the hairs and pinned to the pad circumference.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Figure3-Model_schematic.svg
	width 70line%

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Model"

\end_inset

The capillary bridge model.
 The hairs make contact with the substrate in three ways: a) 
\emph on
In air
\emph default
, where the adhesive fluid bridges are surrounded by air; b) 
\emph on
Underwater: no bubble
\emph default
, where the adhesive fluid bridges are fully surrounded by water; c)
\emph on
 Underwater: bubble
\emph default
, where part of the adhesive fluid bridges are inside the bubble while others
 are outside in water.
 The corresponding ventral view contact images of the beetle's pad are shown
 on the right.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

Let 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{f}=\frac{4}{3}\pi s_{f}^{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{b}=\frac{4}{3}\pi s_{b}^{3}$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{f}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{b}$
\end_inset

 are the radii of spheres with equivalent volumes.
 Fluid and bubble radii are assumed to scale proportional to their corresponding
 pinned contact diameter.
 We thus defined the size parameters, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{f}=D_{h}/\left(2s_{f}\right)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{b}=D_{p}/\left(2s_{b}\right)$
\end_inset

 for the fluid and bubble respectively, to conveniently scale their volumes
 relative to the hair and pad diameters they were pinned to.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The net force for cases 1 and 2 can be calculated as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{net}=Nf\label{eq:f_air/water}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is the capillary force of a single fluid bridge at a distance, 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

, in air (
\begin_inset Formula $f_{air}$
\end_inset

) or underwater (
\begin_inset Formula $f_{water}$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For case 3, the net force is given by:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
F_{net}=N_{in}f_{air}+N_{out}f_{water}+f_{bubble}\label{eq:f_bubble}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{in}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $N_{out}$
\end_inset

 are the number of hairs inside and outside the bubble, respectively, 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{air}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{water}$
\end_inset

 are the capillary forces of the fluid bridge inside and outside the bubble,
 respectively, and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{bubble}$
\end_inset

 is the capillary force contribution due to the bubble meniscus alone at
 distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d+L$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The capillary force, 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

, is the sum of two contributions: surface tension and Laplace pressure.
 Force versus distance for a single capillary bridge is calculated by Surface
 Evolver simulations
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN206"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, (described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Simulation-Method"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and used to obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{net}$
\end_inset

 as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 for each type of contact.
 The adhesion force of the complete hairy pad system is then obtained from
 the minima of 
\begin_inset Formula $F_{net}$
\end_inset

, where negative force values represent attraction.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have considered 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{air}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $f_{water}$
\end_inset

 to be distinct terms because the capillary force by the adhesive fluid
 will be different in air and underwater due to its different contact angle
 and interfacial tension in each case.
 Using the Young-Dupr—ê equations, one can derive the following relation
 for the contact angle of the adhesive fluid underwater:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\cos\theta_{fw}=\frac{\gamma_{fa}\cos\theta_{fa}-\gamma_{wa}\cos\theta_{wa}}{\gamma_{fw}}\label{eq:theta_fw}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{fw}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{fa}$
\end_inset

 are the contact angles of the adhesive fluid with the substrate in water
 and air respectively, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{wa}$
\end_inset

 is the contact angle of water with the substrate in air, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{fa}$
\end_inset

 is the surface tension of the adhesive fluid, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{wa}$
\end_inset

 is the surface tension of water and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{fw}$
\end_inset

 is the interfacial tension of the adhesive fluid with water.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
All lengths are normalized w.r.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{f}$
\end_inset

 and forces are normalized w.r.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{fa}s_{f}$
\end_inset

.
 Interfacial tension values are fixed relative to 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{fa}$
\end_inset

.
 Non dimensional bubble volume is expressed as, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{b}=V_{b}/s_{f}^{3}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Geometric parameters and interfacial properties are kept fixed for all model
 calculations (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Model-parameters"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Here, we assume the adhesive fluid to be an oil-lke substance and thus
 the interfacial tension ratios 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{wa}/\gamma_{fa}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{fw}/\gamma_{fa}$
\end_inset

 are taken corresponding to typical values of oil and water.
 We consider representative hydrophilic and hydrophobic substrates with
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{fa}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{wa}$
\end_inset

 values corresponding to a typical glass and fluorinated surface, respectively.
 Area fraction of the hairs relative to the pad, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=ND_{h}^{2}/D_{p}^{2}$
\end_inset

, hair aspect ratio, 
\begin_inset Formula $L/D_{h}$
\end_inset

, and fluid size parameter, 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{f}$
\end_inset

,
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 are fixed to values typical for a ladybug's hairy pad.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First, we calculate force-distance curves for a single pinned liquid capillary
 bridge.
 Second, the effect of substrate on the force-distance curves of the hairy
 pad system is compared for each type of contact.
 Third, the effect of varying hair diameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{h}$
\end_inset

, on net adhesion is studied.
 Finally, we look at the effect of changing the bubble volume, 
\family roman
\series medium
\shape up
\size normal
\emph off
\bar no
\strikeout off
\xout off
\uuline off
\uwave off
\noun off
\color none

\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{b}$
\end_inset

,
\family default
\series default
\shape default
\size default
\emph default
\bar default
\strikeout default
\xout default
\uuline default
\uwave default
\noun default
\color inherit
 on the net underwater adhesion.
\end_layout

