\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
subcaption{Force contributions}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Single-bridge"

\end_inset

Normalized capillary force of a single liquid bridge in contact with a substrate
 and pinned to a circular perimeter on top.
 Fluid size parameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{f}=2$
\end_inset

.
 Negative force values represents attraction.
 a) Force-distance curves are shown for different contact angles of the
 liquid with the substrate.
 b) Adhesion force, calculated from the minima of the corresponding force-distan
ce curve, is plotted as a function of contact angle with the substrate,
 together with its Laplace and surface tension components (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:f_bridge"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Simulation snapshots of the liquid meniscus corresponding to angles 6¬∞
 and 150¬∞ are depicted.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The force-distance curves show a general trend of being repulsive at small
 distances (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Single-bridge"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

a).
 This is a result of the pinned contact line on the top.
 A limited volume is available for the liquid to occupy when the gap distance
 is small, causing the meniscus shape to bulge outwards near the pinned
 contact line.
 This creates a net positive curvature, resulting in a positive Laplace
 pressure and thus repulsion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Capillary Bridge Model: Effect of the substrate
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Capillary-Bridge-Model:"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The normalized force-distance curves of a hairy pad system on a hydrophilic
 and hydrophobic substrate are predicted based on the capillary bridge model
 and compared for the different contact types (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Effect-of-substrate"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 The forces in each case are calculated from equations 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:f_air/water"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:f_bubble"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 for fixed geometric and interfacial properties (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Model-parameters"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the hydrophilic substrate (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{wa}=24\textdegree$
\end_inset

), contact
\emph on
 in air
\emph default
 shows the highest adhesion.
 
\emph on
Underwater: no bubble
\emph default
 shows close to no adhesion while 
\emph on
underwater: bubble
\emph default
 shows moderate adhesion.
 In contrast, for a hydrophobic substrate (
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{wa}=120\textdegree$
\end_inset

), the highest adhesion is seen for 
\emph on
underwater: no bubble
\emph default
, much larger than 
\emph on
in air
\emph default
.
 Even 
\emph on
underwater: bubble
\emph default
 has slightly higher adhesion than 
\emph on
in air
\emph default
.
 Note that the contact area is fixed by keeping the area fraction and 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}/D_{h}$
\end_inset

 constant.
 All curves correspond to the same total hair contact area.
 Thus, the above mentioned effects are attributed solely to how the the
 capillary force changes in each scenario.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On a hydrophilic substrate, the contact angle of the oily adhesive fluid
 is 6¬∞, when surrounded by air (Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Model-parameters"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

) and 150¬∞, when surrounded by water (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:theta_fw"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 This results in the meniscus shape to have a net negative and slightly
 positive curvatures, respectively, resulting in strong adhesion in air
 and poor adhesion underwater.
 On a hydrophobic substrate however, the contact angles of the fluid in
 air and water are 50¬∞ and 1¬∞, respectively.
 In both cases, the contact angles are low, resulting in strong adhesion
 in both media.
 Additionally, the interfacial tension of the oily fluid underwater (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{fw}$
\end_inset

) is twice that of in air (
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{fa}$
\end_inset

).
 Thus, we see a higher capillary adhesion for the 
\emph on
underwater: no bubble
\emph default
 case when compared to 
\emph on
in air
\emph default
 (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Oil-contact-images"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Figure5-Model_effect_of_substrate.svg
	lyxscale 50

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Effect-of-substrate"

\end_inset

Theoretical force-distance curves of a hairy pad system on a hydrophilic
 and hydrophobic substrate in air and underwater conditions.
 A negative force value represents attraction.
 Normalized forces are calculated from the capillary bridge model, with
 model parameters listed in Table 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "tab:Model-parameters"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

.
 The bubble's contribution to the net force for an 
\emph on
underwater: bubble
\emph default
 contact is denoted by plus symbols.
 Insets represent the 
\emph on
underwater: bubble 
\emph default
contact for each substrate.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The net force in the 
\emph on
underwater: bubble
\emph default
 case mainly depends on the proportion of hairs inside and outside the bubble
 (equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:f_bubble"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 For the given bubble volume, only part of the hairs are inside the bubble
 for the hydrophilic substrate, while, all the hairs are inside the bubble
 for the hydrophobic substrate.
 Therefore, the force curve lies between 
\emph on
in air
\emph default
 and 
\emph on
underwater: no bubble
\emph default
 cases for a hydrophilic substrate, and closely follows the 
\emph on
in air
\emph default
 case for a hydrophobic substrate.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The contribution of the capillary force due to the bubble itself is negligible
 for both substrates (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Effect-of-substrate"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Its contribution even is slightly repulsive on the hydrophilic substrate
 due to the positive curvature of the bubble, and slightly attractive on
 the hydrophobic substrate due to its negative curvature.
 This small contribution is manifested by the slightly higher adhesion for
 
\emph on
underwater: bubble
\emph default
 relative to 
\emph on
in air
\emph default
 for the hydrophobic substrate, since all hairs are within the bubble in
 this case.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Capillary Bridge Model: Effect of bubble volume
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effect of varying bubble volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{b}$
\end_inset

, on the net adhesion force of the 
\emph on
underwater: bubble
\emph default
 case are compared for hydrophilic and hydrophobic substrates (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Effect-of-bubble"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 From previous section, we know that on the hydrophilic substrate, fluid
 bridges outside the bubble show poor adhesion due to the positive curvature
 of their meniscus.
 Thus, decreasing 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{b}$
\end_inset

 decreases the adhesion force due to a larger proportion of hairs being
 outside the bubble.
 In contrast, on the hydrophobic substrate, fluid bridges outside the bubble
 show higher capillary forces, due to its low contact angle and high interfacial
 tension in water.
 Thus, adhesion force increases for a hydrophobic substrate as the bubble
 size decreases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Figure7-Model_effect_of_bubble_volume.svg

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:Effect-of-bubble"

\end_inset

Normalized adhesion force of a hairy pad system as a function of bubble
 volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{b}$
\end_inset

, for the 
\emph on
underwater: bubble
\emph default
 contact type.
 Adhesion forces are calculated from the minima of the respective force-distance
 curves.
 Negative force value represents attraction.
 Pad to hair diameter ratio (
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}/D_{h}$
\end_inset

) is kept fixed.
 Highlighted regions represent entrapment of all hairs within the bubble.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

The contribution of the bubble to the net adhesion force is small regardless
 of its volume, when compared to the whole pad.
 We see that a smaller 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{b}$
\end_inset

 results in increased attraction by the bubble on both types of substrates.
 For larger values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{b}$
\end_inset

, the force trend for the whole pad mostly follows that of the bubble, because
 the bubble in this case is big enough to entrap all the hairs inside it.
 Thus, the force contribution due to the fluid bridges remain unchanged,
 and only the bubble's contribution drives the slight variation in the pad's
 adhesion at high 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{b}$
\end_inset

.
 Once the bubble is small enough such that part of the fluid bridges start
 making contact in water, the force trend changes, with a steep decrease
 (increase) in adhesion force on hydrophilic (hydrophobic) substrate as
 the volume decreases.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Capillary Bridge Model: Effect of hair diameter 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The effect of changing hair diameter, 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{h}$
\end_inset

, to the net adhesion force is compared for hydrophilic and hydrophobic
 substrates (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Effect-of-hair"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Here, the pad diameter, total hair contact area and bubble volume are constant
 since 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{V}_{b}$
\end_inset

 are kept fixed.
 The radius corresponding to the fluid volume is assumed to scale proportional
 to the hair diameter and is fixed (
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_{f}=2$
\end_inset

).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Adhesion force increases with decreasing 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{h}$
\end_inset

 for both hydrophilic and hydrophobic substrates in all contact types.
 This is consistent with the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

contact splitting
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 theory, which predicts higher adhesion when the contact is split into many
 small contact points
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN24"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 Reducing the hair diameter results in two competing effects: 1) capillary
 force due to a single fluid bridge decreases due to its smaller size and
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

self-similar
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 scaling assumption (
\begin_inset Formula $f\sim D_{h}$
\end_inset

), which decreases the net force, and 2) total number of fluid bridges increases
 since the total hair contact area is assumed to be fixed (
\begin_inset Formula $N\sim1/D_{h}^{2}$
\end_inset

), which increases the net force.
 The second effect dominates, resulting in a higher adhesion force as 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{h}$
\end_inset

 decreases.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename Figure6-Model_effect_of_hair_size.svg
	lyxscale 50
	scale 50

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
