 This work was funded by 
\emph on
Deutsche Forschungsgemeinschaft
\emph default
 (Grant number: PI 1351/2-1).
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
\start_of_appendix
Appendix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Simulation method: Single capillary bridge 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Simulation-Method"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
setcounter{figure}{0} 
\backslash
renewcommand{
\backslash
thefigure}{A.
\backslash
arabic{figure}} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
setcounter{equation}{0} 
\backslash
renewcommand{
\backslash
theequation}{A.
\backslash
arabic{equation}} 
\end_layout

\end_inset

Capillary force due to a single adhesive fluid or bubble meniscus (termed
 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

capillary bridge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) is calculated by performing simulations in Surface Evolver 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN206"
literal "false"

\end_inset

, similar to the method described by De Souza et.
 al.
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "RN93"
literal "false"

\end_inset

.
 A simple cubic geometry, mimicking the capillary bridge, of constant volume,
 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

, is defined as the initial condition with an interfacial tension, 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

, with the surrounding medium.
 Interfacial tension of the capillary bridge with the substrate is given
 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma\cos\theta$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding contact angle inside the bridge.
 For the case of a bubble meniscus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 is defined w.r.t.
 the surrounding water, since 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

 can also directly characterize the substrate wettability.
 The capillary bridge spans a gap distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 between the top face and the substrate.
 The boundary conditions are set corresponding to a pinned contact line
 of diameter 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 on the top face and constant interfacial tension with the substrate on
 the bottom.
 All lengths are normalized relative to length 
\begin_inset Formula $s=\left(3V/4\pi\right)^{1/3}$
\end_inset

.
 An appropriate geometry refinement routine is chosen to evolve the capillary
 bridge shape to its minimum energy state.
 The normalized total capillary force, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{f}=f/\gamma s$
\end_inset

, is the sum of the Laplace pressure and surface tension contributions ,
 where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
f=f_{laplace}+f_{surface\,tension}=\varDelta P_{laplace}A_{_{bottom}}+2\pi R_{bottom}\gamma\sin\theta\label{eq:f_bridge}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varDelta P_{laplace}$
\end_inset

 is the Laplace pressure of the equilibrium capillary bridge, 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{bottom}$
\end_inset

 is the contact area of the capillary bridge with the substrate at bottom
 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{bottom}$
\end_inset

 is the corresponding radius of contact, all obtained from the simulation
 output for the equilibrium surface.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The gap distance 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is varied stepwise and the capillary force is calculated each time to obtain
 force-distance curves for a particular choice of 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Single capillary bridge: Effect of volume
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Surface Evolver simulation results showing the effect of volume on the maximum
 capillary force of a single fluid bridge.
 Since the fluid is pinned at the top to the same diameter, D, a smaller
 volume would result in high interfacial curvatures, which increases the
 capillary force due to the negative Laplace pressure.
 In this case, small contact angles lead to a greater increase in adhesion.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Float figure
wide false
sideways false
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Graphics
	filename FigureS2-Effect_of_fluid_volume.svg

\end_inset


\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Normalized maximum capillary force for a single bridge as a function of
 fluid volume
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Capillary Bridge Model: Effect of hair diameter at constant fluid volume
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Here, instead of scaling the fluid volume relative to the hair diameter,
 we now assume a fixed total fluid volume distributed equally among the
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 hairs.
 Total fluid volume, 
\begin_inset Formula $V_{total}=NV_{f}=2000$
\end_inset

.
 Hair diameter is varied while keeping the total hair contact area constant.
 Length is in arbitrary units.
 Forces increase at a much smaller rate on decreasing diameter when compared
 to the case with self-similar scaling of fluid volume (Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:Effect-of-hair"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
\end_layout

