\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
Normalized adhesion force of hairy pad system on a hydrophilic and hydrophobic
 substrate as a function of hair diameter (
\begin_inset Formula $D_{h}$
\end_inset

), calculated from the capillary bridge model.
 The total adhesive fluid volume is fixed to 2000.
 Adhesion forces are calculated from minima of the respective force-distance
 curves.
 Negative force value represents attraction.
 The bubble's contribution to the net force for an 
\emph on
underwater: bubble
\emph default
 contact is denoted by plus symbols.
 Bubble volume and pad diameter are kept fixed.
 All lengths are scaled relative to 
\begin_inset Formula $D_{p}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Capillary force due to a bubble
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:Capillary-force-due"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Capillary force of a single bubble against a PFOTS surface are compared
 for two different volumes.
 The volumes correspond to the expected range in the case of the trapped
 bubble in a ladybug.
 Here, the bubble is pinned to a micropatterned PDMS substrate on the top.
 The maximum adhesion force of any of the bubble never exceeds 50 ŒºN, significan
tly lower than the beetle's underwater adhesion to the same substrate (>
 400 ŒºN).
 Thus, the bubble's contribution to adhesion in the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset


\emph on
underwater: bubble
\emph default

\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 contact of a ladybug's pad should be negligible.
\end_layout

